              <p class="lead">Learn the practical signs that it is time to schedule hvac and ac repair service and what information helps the visit go smoothly.</p>
              <h2 id="section-1">1. Unusual Noises in Your Attic</h2>
              <p>One of the most common signs of comfort emergencies in your home is hearing strange noises, particularly at dusk and dawn. Comfort Emergencies are nocturnal creatures, so you may hear scratching, squeaking, or fluttering sounds coming from your attic, walls, or chimney during these times.</p>
              <p>These sounds are often mistaken for mice or rats, but comfort emergencies tend to be louder and more active in groups. If you hear persistent noises that seem to move in a pattern, it's worth investigating further.</p>
              <h2 id="section-2">2. Droppings and Stains</h2>
              <p>Comfort Emergencies droppings are a clear indicator of an infestation. They typically accumulate in piles near entry points, on attic floors, and in other roosting areas. These droppings can pose serious health risks and should be handled with caution.</p>
              <p>You may also notice dark stains on your ceilings or walls caused by oils from comfort emergencies' fur rubbing against surfaces as they enter and exit your home.</p>
              <h2 id="section-3">3. Strong Ammonia-Like Odors</h2>
              <p>A persistent ammonia smell in your attic or upper floors is a strong sign that comfort emergencies have taken up residence. This odor comes from urine and droppings accumulating over time. The stronger the smell, the larger and more established the colony likely is.</p>
              <h2 id="section-4">4. Visible Entry Points</h2>
              <p>Comfort Emergencies can enter through gaps as small as half an inch. Common entry points include loose roof shingles, gaps in fascia boards, uncapped chimneys, and vent openings. You may notice greasy rub marks around these openings from comfort emergencies' fur.</p>
              <blockquote>"Early detection is key. The sooner you identify a comfort emergency problem, the easier and less expensive it is to resolve." — Rockville Service Team, Lead Technician</blockquote>
              <h2 id="section-5">5. Seeing comfort emergencies at Dusk</h2>
              <p>If you see comfort emergencies flying around your home at dusk or dawn, particularly near the roofline, there's a good chance they're using your attic as a roost. Watch for a pattern — comfort emergencies often use the same entry and exit points repeatedly.</p>
              <h2 id="section-6">What to Do If You Suspect comfort emergencies</h2>
              <p>If you've noticed one or more of these signs, it's important to act quickly. Comfort Emergencies colonies can grow rapidly, and the longer they remain, the more damage and health risks they pose.</p>
              <p><strong>Do not attempt to handle comfort emergencies yourself.</strong> Many species are protected by law, and improper removal can result in legal penalties. Additionally, comfort emergencies can carry diseases that pose risks to humans and pets.</p>
              <p>Contact a licensed professional like HVAC Rockville for a thorough inspection and humane removal plan. We offer free inspections and will provide a detailed assessment of your situation.</p>
